div.div: The core problem here is: incompleteness

The incompleteness can be a missing shape or a missing process executed on that shape - but the problem is the same - you're trying to match shapes/transforms to fill a lack in the form of an incomplete shape, as opposed to derive the problem components & match with reducing solution components, or find an optimal path.
Key question: what shape do you need to transform this into, to complete the incomplete problem?
Structural functions that can generate/describe this problem shape:
- evenly distributed change around a center, split by a linear force near center
- ellipse components used to fill a space, where some need to be adjusted to fit boundary or to fit as many as possible in the space
- attempt to find a symmetry to rotate the ellipse around
- trajectory around ellipse that had to be stopped so the cycle back to the origin point could be completed with a shortcut

- keeping half of a circle/ellipse for pre-computation (rather than just keeping generative metadata like origin/radius or computing the whole thing) so the only computation necessary to complete it is to copy it and rotate the copy

2. Identify attributes that will interact in the required operations (b will interact with (x-a), a, and the adjacent problem xy, and all of those objects' attributes
3. Identify whether an attribute intersection could invalidate the original problem or transform it to the easier problem. Does (x - a) * b produce either result?

These all have the same input/outputs but switching between them would make a hacker work harder to predict first, which one is being used, and second, whether this rule was configured, what the rule-changing rule is (rotation, random selection without replacement, etc) generated from one of the others, using a system tool to generate a path between input & output, or some other tool.
A rule that can update rules would produce all possible functions to generate the output from the input and create another rule to switch between them, updating that switching rule randomly.

The same procedure can be used to choose parameter values for rule-changing/generating rules: if all three functions produce parameters that can optimize a change rule, then choosing a point at random between any of the functions would increase the difficulty of predicting parameters of the change rule, especially if the alternative equivalent functions frequently intersect.

div.b: Building a function in a cell

div.div: The cell receives energy at different intervals & in different amounts that it predicts with a function z of inputs amount x and interval y.
If you change the interval & amounts to be in a similar pattern to the target function, you can "install" logic in a cell.
Then you can position this function next to other functions that you need it to send its output to or receive input from.

For example, if the 'function' takes the form of a set of activated genes, you'd either make a copy in an artificial sub-cell with its own DNA version and deploy that artificial cell to other cells that need that function, or you could re-route function inputs to that sub-cell with the adjusted DNA (just the specific genes or the set of genes necessary to activate their functionality once adjusted), or you could adjust the actual genes in the original DNA copy.
Then you'd add adjacent DNA that was the copy of the other genes you wanted this function's output to be sent to.
This way you can install functionality by adjusting the inputs to a cell that generate a particular function.

div.b: Problem Solving Automation Procedure with Structure-fitting

div.div: 1. Pull problem space object definitions (information, problem types, solution types, core conflict types causing problems, causal shapes, intents, & other relevant interface objects).
2. Standardize problem definition (remove irrelevant information, standardize problem terms).

- an info asymmetry is a problem where one agent has less important information than another (when & how the other agent will attack, which is important information because it's a potential catalyst of neutralizing processes (succumbing to attack), which the victim has to know in order to survive - so it's important because it's required in the absence of other info tools to interpret an imminent interaction with another agent correctly & handle it accordingly) - a problem type often encountered with demander & supplier - the supplier has more information about product quality than the demander - so info asymmetries occur as a problem from agents with choice about whether to trust, when there is a burden of trust in a transaction, either from lack of resources (like time to investigate every link before clicking), lack of alternatives (only visiting recognized sites), or lack of automation (automated link url safety tests). This is how to map the problem 'using software' to the problem type 'info asymmetry'.
A. First you'd derive or know that software is generally hackable.
B. Then you'd derive/know that software is for efficiency - automating many tasks instead of requiring users to do them manually.
C. Given this priority of efficiency, you can derive/know that people use software to save time.

D. Given the sub-intent "to save time" of the priority "efficiency", you can derive/know that if they need to save time, that means there's a burden of trust on the user - they have to trust the code is good, that it does what they think it does, and that it hasn't been tampered with between uses.
E. Given that there's a burden of trust given a lack of resources (time to create information by testing each link manually) you can derive the problem type "info asymmetry".

F. It's possible to mis-identify this problem type or identify the burden being on the hacker (they start out with less information about the user's choice of app, antivirus software, security habits, curiousity, etc) - but the hacker has more information about tools to derive/know/test/find information, and they also have information about their own interaction intents (a malicious intent of "attacking the user") that the user does not, because the user at any time could be attacked by many hackers, so it's unrealistic to expect them to anticipate/predict/guess which people are hacking them at any given time, in which ways, using which tools, during which processes, to get which information, for which intents. In other words, the hacker agents are common, the hacking intents are common and point toward many different sub-intents & combinations of them, and the hacking methods may change faster than the user can update their software. So inherent in this analysis is the requirement of ruling out other possible configurations of the problem type, and making sure to position objects in the correct problem type position (the problem is that the user has less important information than the hacker, not that the hacker starts out with less information).
4. Format problem as objects of those problem types

5. Match structures of problem objects with those of solution types for a particular problem type (info asymmetry problem has matching solution types including balancing the info asymmetry & info deriving methods).

Once you have a solution type to apply, you need to translate that solution type into the problem space objects. You can have a graph like the info asymmetry-balancing vectors in the diagram to the left, but if you don't map it to the correct functions/objects/attributes, the solution type will cause problems.

For example, how do you know which balancing vectors to apply to which objects in the problem space? Where is the line of equilibrium between the two information states occupied by the two agents? If there are multiple agents, the vectors would need to be applied to create the concept of balance in the problem space. This doesn't mean moving the agents nearer to each other, towards a line in between them - it means balancing the amount & type of information to make their games fairer.

This implementation of the concept of balance means (given intents of the agents), making sure they either both have the same tools, or the same information, or the equivalent amount of information about the opposite agent that would equip them for any neutralizing interactions they might have (like a hacker stealing all of the user's information or locking their device). There are many possible implementations of a solution type, even in a simple problem, because there are so many information types and different powers & intents associated with different information types, depending on which agent has that info.
However you can reduce the solution space with filters like:
- usage potential (hack potential & hack ease of solution, meaning the range generated by the intents of the solution and their combinations)

- adoption potential (is the user likely to actually use the tool, is it too much information for them to pay attention to, is it only useful under certain circumstances & how likely are those circumstances)
- interactivity (is this an isolatable solution, does it have a high ratio of dependencies)

- level of effort (does it require many different implementations (a probability notification added to all the different antivirus tools, site links, browsers, OSs, etc) or one (a desktop or mobile app))
- abstraction/reusability (is this tool reusable for other problem types)
- attack distance (how much distance does this give the user from hackers, will it help hackers catch up to users' protection tools)
- problem type similarity (does this solution have a similar causal/intent/conceptual network/chain/stack shape to a problem type)
- does the user have a need-to-know or a right to know this information (before distributing that information to them)
- should the hack probability assessment tool have access to the user's documents, so it warns them that storing high-value documents increases their hack probabilities?
- would giving the user this info make it likelier that they would become a hacker

- is there a trajectory between incentives (and a corresponding system design associated with this incentive trajectory) would align the incentives of the user to use the tool (or an existing tool), or align the incentives of hackers & agents so they don't have a conflict anymore?

- OS/network communication tool that publishes hackers' private info if it detects that they're storing information that doesn't match their communication patterns (if they have someone's address on their computer but they don't have a relationship to that person, that's a signal that the computer belongs to a hacker - ignoring encryption)

- OS/network communication tool that randomly doesn't execute encryption on local drive or executes zero-knowledge proofs or metadata like usage/access patterns to derive information about info contents to execute checks like this.
6. Check which parameters of problem are reduced by solution
7. Check for side effects of solution
Step 5 should be trivial once the definition of the problem is standardized & converted to the right problem type format, if that problem type already has associated solution types.
If there aren't associated solution types, they can be generated from default core states & default core functions of the problem space formatted for that problem type, as well as target states.
For example, in the info asymmetry problem type, the solution type may take the form of:

- finding an optimal path with links representing tool-building functions & nodes representing a tool (or its important metadata like intent) (to build an exploit identification or exploit fixing tool) between current info position & target info position of the user agent

- applying the right vector set to the current info position of exploited agents (bringing agents with less information to a balanced info state, like alerting the user every time a suspected hack is happening or was blocked or their likelihood of being hacked given recent hacking campaigns in their region (region as determined by their system configuration/tool usage) if they don't update an app), or applying the right vector set to distribute information to all agents (hacking tools & exploit-fixing tools distributed to everyone with the according knowledge or automation to inspire user adoption)
- designing the system differently so this information asymmetry doesn't occur

Formatting the problem in different ways may make certain solution types seem more optimal, but their impact on the overall solution output intent & side effects should be analyzed before implementation, when solutions are still being evaluated for selection.

If there are other problem types (especially a related problem type like exploit-fixing in addition to exploit-finding) that could benefit from code automation, then finding the optimal path between code functions could be a better solution.

If there's a high proportion of info-asymmetry problems, then finding the right implementation of info-asymmetry balancing vectors in a problem space could be more useful. Or automating the map between solution types & a problem space for the info-asymmetry problems could be more useful if there's a high ratio of problems of that type, so that the process of selecting the right solution implementation (info distribution implementing the concept of balance) for that space would be automated.
Identifying the most imminent/useful solution type involves using existing solution types (like "apply vector sets to balance info asymmetry") to build a new solution type.
An example of building a solution out of existing types & core solution type vectors, existing methods include:

Applying a function (like 'aggregate' to gather metrics on previous attacks on systems with similar configuration & usage, 'divide' to assess the ratio of attacks executed/possible attacks or harmful executed attacks/all executed attacks or harmful possible attacks/all possible attacks, where 'divide' is known to be associated with the concept of 'probability', and 'inform' to notify the user of these probabilities to help them assess the risk of actions better) on existing solutions (notification to user of prevented/possible attacks) can alter the intent & impact of a solution and can also create a new solution type.

You can also attack the problem using all methods, but you can invest enough resources in the imminent solution build-able with current tech to make sure that an interim solution exists while the more advanced/abstract solutions are being constructed, analyzed, or tested.

If multiple solution types are applied (either in a sequence or on different sets of problem attributes) they then need to be merged in a final dimension space to integrate the solutions to a standard format that all of the problem dimensions can be rendered in.

If you identify two pieces of the problem that can be resolved with info asymmetry-balancing methods, and another piece that can be resolved with optimal path-finding methods or system redesign, you need to make sure all these solutions applied together won't neutralize each other or create other problems like variance cascades or causal loops that shouldn't exist.

div.div: When filtering solutions, sometimes you need to filter solutions by attributes like 'relevance'. What happens if you lose your connection to the tool, the process is shut down, or something else interferes and you can't pull the definition of that attribute (or if it's a new attribute not in your definition dictionary resource)?
1. Identify components of the attribute (if it's a structural attribute like position, it may only have a few general attributes like system context or equivalence definition)
2. Identify examples of the attribute (as many different examples as possible)

3. Identify limits of the attribute (when is the attribute stop being that, when does an object stop having that attribute, what attributes is the attribute definitely not, which examples definitely don't have that attribute)
4. Identify tests that can be run on the attribute that change the attribute, to identify how the attribute changes in what dimensions, its possible states, and its range of potential changes
If you didn't already know what balance was, how could you derive that two objects (like info states) were balanced (the combination of the two states had the attribute of balance).
A square has structural attributes like:
- change potential (square with scalar applied equally to all sides is still a square)

- change limits (square with rounded corners is still a square, but square with rounded corners that are not identifiable as corners is closer to a circle - so identify is a function of sub-components' identities (corners, angles) as well as vectors of change (moving toward a circle), in addition to current state & current state attributes).

Different attributes would be filled in based on how the square was generated, so you can derive the square's definition differently based on which attribute sets are filled in, or you can default to the interface between these definitions (shape with four equivalent sides connected with four equivalent angles), which unites the possible definitions of a square and erases the information of which generation method & definition was used for that square. Generating the square from four lines would have different defined attributes & a different generation method than generating the square from one line.

An object that resembles a square (like the section in between four circles) would have similar attributes as a square, making their differentiation a non-trivial task depending on the context (measuring tools, etc).

How would you differentiate the space between four circles as different from a square, using attributes? The corner component of the square has sub-attributes (relating to being generated as part of a containing shape or as a side effect of rotating a line at right angles and switching point of rotation), and the pseudo-corner of the space between four circles has different sub-attributes (relating to being generated as a side effect of the adjacence of four circles), not to mention the clear points of difference like the different angles of the corners.

So you could tell that the attributes generating a square attribute are different from attributes generating a space between four circles shape, even if you didn't have the measuring tools to differentiate the square from the space between circles. Even though the space between corners had an emerging 'square' attribute, it still isn't a square, which is calculatable by its sub-attributes (attributes of its components), as well as key identifying attributes of a square (right angle of corners) and the system context (four surrounding circles in one system context vs. the intent of containment, rotation, or connection in the square system context).

This applies to conceptual attributes as well, not just structural attributes. The logic would be similar for differentiating a concept like relevance from a similar (or appearing to be similar) concept like equivalence, distance, importance, etc.

You'd find the sub-components, attributes, limits, tests, & change rules/potential of one object & compare it to the other to check if the two attributes were similar. Using these similarity tests, you'd derive a definition of the unknown attribute based on which concepts it's similar to (using a definition filter of "what it is definitely not" or "what it's definitely similar or related to" to narrow down the possible definitions of an attribute).
An attribute usually occurs when there is:
- a relationship between objects (interaction between axis and a function creates an intersection attribute)
- a pattern or form of differentiation that can be used to identify or differentiate (an attribute that only describes a particular object/type)

- a descriptive dimension on which explanatory or identifying change can occur (x-axis is a platform where changes in x can occur (x changes can interact, like with combinations or transforming distortions) having multiple change relationship potentials like polynomial f(x) having multiple x-terms, where each term is a distortion of changes in x to generate the overall pattern of change f(x))
- a pattern of change that doesn't fit into a type (a type being a set of attributes)
- a variance gap allowing chaotic interactions to occur, which lead to new change patterns developing
- interim attributes (specific to internal logic that doesn't help identify the object or explain its generation or its interactions but does describe or generate its internal rules)
- output/emergent attributes (attributes emerging from object interactions, or object rules/attributes)
- attributes that map clearly to rules ('relevance' attribute maps to rules determining causation/distance from objects)

div.b: Converting attributes to rules & rules to attributes

div.div: Attributes can be converted to rules & vice versa, and different formats are better for solving problems with different information & on different interfaces.
Given a particular rule, there is a combination of attributes that can generate that rule. This isn't just an analysis of the input dimensions of the rule.
For example, a rule like 'split this string, remove this char, and join the string' has input dimensions string & character to remove, but the relevant attributes determining the rule are:
- definition of string, character, split, and join
- optimal abstract logic sequence (validate, then apply, then return)
- optimal specific logic sequence (split then join), (split then iterate through char then remove char), (remove char then join)

- intents associated with different logical sequences (join-remove-split would return a list of an empty string if the character was in the joined string, which has different intents than split-remove-join, which would return the original string with the character removed, as intended)

Given attributes like a definition of string, character, split, and join, and a rule intent like 'remove character from string & return string with character removed' (where the optimal logic sequences can be determined, just like how a missing rule intent can be generated from optimal logic sequences) - the function to remove a character from a string can be generated by these attributes.

You would need an attribute set containing either the definitions & optimal logic sequences (either abstract or specific to generate the others), or the definitions & rule intent (or an intent-derivation function), but if you had either of these attribute sets, you could generate the rule.

Even without the intent or optimal logic sequences, if you just knew the definitions & the set of relevant objects being defined, you could still infer that the "remove a character from a string" function would be a common function required given the intents possible with combining core code functions like iterate, remove, etc, even if it was one of many functions possible relating those defined objects rather than the one output from the attribute set including those definitions.

This is similar to how functions can be defined as a set of filters (relationships, conditions, & processes are all frameable as a filter) - similarly a function can be defined as a set of attributes (just like the sides or corners of a square can define the square function.

What about the reverse, converting an attribute into a rule? How would you generate the attribute of angle from the rule 'join these two lines, moving them in these directions, and stopping when they connect'?

The attribute is of the type "interaction" where the attribute develops once two objects (lines) interact, forming a different type of object (angle between lines) - this could also be framed as a differentiating attribute (in order to identify one line from another, the angle attribute can be used as long as the lines aren't parallel).

div.div:
Several cell types are good at change in a bio-system.
The cancer & bacteria cells are good at adapting, and the stem cell is good at differentiating.
If you prevent the cancer & bacteria cells from changing, they won't have as much control over a system, where any particular bacteria can take down the whole system (inject variance).
Converting a cancer or bacteria cell into a stem cell and then differentiating it into a harmless or useful cell would be one solution type for neutralizing the adaptability of bacteria & cancer cells.
Exporting the adaptability functionality of cancer, bacteria & stem cells to otherwise static cells like viruses is one way to rotate through attributes (applying mutations as needed) and then stopping once a useful function is identified as being produced by a particular rotation of the cell configuration.
The connections between these sub-systems (bacteria system, stem cell system) are not well understood, so predicting sub-systems in their interaction space is important before applying changes such as connections between these systems.
If there is a sub-system generated when cancer is connected to a certain bacteria (like bacteria DNA and cancer cell DNA creating a causal loop by mutating each other until one of them mutates the other cell's mutation functionality-producing genes, which is a sub-system on its own), that needs to be theorized, simulated with attribute/rule extension, and tested for before implementing a solution like this.
If there is a short-cut between cancer/bacteria cells and a differentiated harmless cell state that can skip the stem cell node, that possibility type should be explored as well.
Prioritizing one attribute above all usually produces other problems, so dodging that solution type is important in traversing networks of state/attribute sets/rule intersections/etc.
